A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow down the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works for the viruses that have already gained immunity against the drugs.
This fact outweighs in some cases that the compound does not feel as strong on the common variant of the virus as it does for some of the drugs already available.
AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, patients can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, the incomplete suppression of the virus's propagation results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which the drugs are no longer inactive.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Chemistry in Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called methocarrborates act on the protein responsible for the HIV multiplication.
Metalocarborates are boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt compounds.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all the drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new 'enhancements' compounds prepared by the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metalocarkorkhates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyheddron cages made up of the atoms of the boron, hydrogen and carbon are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
