Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday decided to annul the country's main pro-Kurdish party. This decision immediately triggered protest demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of a government that seeks to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society (DTP) party was dissolved because it became "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Chief Justice Chief Justice Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority-seven votes to be dissolved, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president, Ahmet Türk, and MEP Aysela Tugluk, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity of Mr Türk and Ms Tugluk and the confiscation of the assets of the party by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 500).
The party's leadership had already warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than act as political-affiliated MPs.
The decision is a continuation of the trial initiated in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation, Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, accusing the DTP of obedience to the "gures" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organisation.
Many observers believe that the DTP is a legal political case for the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has no "fundative association" with the PKK, but refuses to label it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court's verdict comes as the government gives the Kurdish community a friendly hand, offering a series of measures to strengthen their rights and attempt to limit the support of the Kurds against the PKK to end the conflict.
DTP leadership has confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to a resumption of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations have turned to the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is being held to clashes with the police.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of demonstrators have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast that are inhabited mainly by the Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water cannons, and the demonstrators threw Molotov cocktails or fired stones from slingshots.
Also in Istanbul, about a hundred people were demonstrating.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the justice decision would only "defeuce despair."
